Title: Generating Process Explanations in Nuclear Astrophysics  
Author: Pat Langley 
Keyword: scientific discovery, astrophysics, reaction pathways, process explanations  
Note: Contact author: Pat Langley, langley@newatlantis.isle.org, (650) 494-3884  
Address: 2164 Staunton Court, Palo Alto, CA 94306 USA Sakir Kocabas  ITU, 80626 Maslak, Istanbul, Turkey  
Affiliation: Institute for the Study of Learning and Expertise  Department of Space Sciences and Technology  
Abstract: In this paper we describe ASTRA, a computational aid for generating process explanations in nuclear astrophysics. The system operates in two stages, the first using knowledge of quantum theory to produce a set of legal reactions among elements and the second searching for pathways of such reactions that explain the evolution of some element in terms of lighter ones. ASTRA has found apparently novel reactions that involve proton and neutron capture, as well as novel fusion reactions that produce neutrons and deuterium. The system has also generated reaction pathways for helium, carbon, and oxygen that do not appear in the scientific literature. Discussions with an expert in the domain suggest these results have scientific merit. However, ASTRA also finds many other reaction pathways that are less interesting and that point toward directions for future research. 
